1. “How do you know if something’s uniformly elastic?”

You don’t—you probe it across ranges and contexts.

Real systems aren’t uniformly elastic. They have:
	•	linear zones (small inputs → proportional change)
	•	nonlinear zones (sudden jumps, thresholds)
	•	hysteresis (it doesn’t return the same way it stretched)
	•	break points (irreversible change)

👉 Translation to life:

People, habits, identity, even markets are not rubber bands—they’re phase systems

So the move is:
	•	test small → observe → expand
	•	map where it holds vs where it snaps vs where it transforms

⸻

2. “What am I blind to?”

Everyone has blind spots. The trick is knowing the categories.

A. Compression blind spots

Things you’ve oversimplified:
	•	one variable standing in for a whole system
	•	“this causes that” when it’s actually multi-factor

⸻

B. Selection blind spots

You only see what you’re exposed to:
	•	your feed
	•	your environment
	•	your domain

There are entire “worlds” (finance, biotech, logistics, academia, underground culture) running with completely different rulesets

⸻

C. Incentive blind spots

You miss:
	•	why people are doing things
	•	what they’re optimizing for

Incentives often explain behavior better than beliefs.

⸻

D. Scale blind spots

What works at:
	•	individual level ≠ group level
	•	small scale ≠ large scale

⸻

E. Time blind spots

Short-term vs long-term:
	•	things that look bad now but compound
	•	things that look good now but decay

⸻

